<subSubSection id="F1E3F1205E9B62CCF7BFE90B01E30242" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="40569B0DD497837852AF8CD7937DA4E4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E2C915A73600485A87E20D5F3A4B97D" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
A small species of 
<taxonomicName id="D2BEC467D5530FFA6780C2189704DC9C" authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1833" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E72410E3F2A97FFB382BA84C79B24387" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a spiral sculpture of small threads and faint riblets crossing the spirals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A6FB8A51EA5E60E8297DA44DBF272442" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph id="2C679E490EA64AAF34C2C2F881819DE1" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1AE5AE12E13CEC9D86885827A034D81E" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">The shell colour is pale whitish, with a broadly depressed spire. The protoconch is broadly enlarged and sculptured by fine spiral threads. The whorls of the teleoconch are narrow and increase regularly, suture of medium depth. The last whorl is broadened, non-descending, well rounded. The surface of the teleoconch is sculptured by fine widely spaced riblets. The spiral sculpture of the protoconch continues on the teleoconch whorls and becomes stronger, dissecting the riblets and giving them a fine granulated appearance. On the subsurface, the riblets become faint while the spiral sculpture increases in strength.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F2E70879D25160BAEEF6DEADCA832616" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">The umbilicus is of medium width and funnel-shaped to cylindriform.</paragraph>
<caption id="E658B582B25DFFD0E7AF42BCA41A9FB2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/14964" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="3B0F646E32FD1CB76BF2943982FC0839" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="3B53225702CFDE2C8896E442E83C2CA1" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="5AC06B31CF2D49377039BFA364F5E43B" authorityName="Gümüş &amp; Neubert" authorityYear="2012" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gostelii">
<emphasis id="711178D8384E13AE20582F9DD416A49D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea gostelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n., D = 2.25 mm. - All figures scaled 
<normalizedToken id="810884232502E297F773C3337C854F1B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
20, phot H. Baur, NMBE.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E71B77DD30B420CAE8EA51D2EE8ADB86" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="measurements">
<paragraph id="ED2F9E54F965EE1844818C92A6045AC0" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Measurements.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BC1EE9193AE0FA60D962D87A72B5D1C4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Holotype: H = 1.29; D = 2.25; PH = not measured because of damage of shell; PD = 1.05; W = 4.75.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="27D2654171BB13ACCD301B45BE9569D4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="58D856ACEDBA50D25F068E572B455ED6" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="79CC578AF93704D158A87E10427F6223" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
(
<figureCitation id="791498EC22BDD55956617A3F73061E75" captionStart="Figure 29" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 29. Distribution map. ▲ Vitrea gostelii sp. n. ● Turanena demirsoyi sp. n. and Rhabdoena gostelii sp. n. ■ Euchondrus paucidentatus sp. n. ▼ Metafruticicola kizildagensis sp. n. ► Assyriella thospitis menkhorsti ssp. n." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/14977" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
): Hitherto, only the holotype is known from the type locality in the 
<normalizedToken id="E16103952BDF2064A9B4D1DE2CFC4163" originalValue="Kaş">Kas</normalizedToken>
area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="79CFA96DAA0EC9A8FDAF6373ED85A9A4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3B2FFE40381BF00B6B10CC0A3EF6CE32" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1BAFA27B7B8E9A117765725D8789BDF" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">This new species is dedicated to our dear friend, the late Dr. Margret Gosteli from the Natural History Museum Berne, Switzerland. She very much enjoyed our joint visit to Turkey in 2006 and was eager to work about the malacofauna of Turkey.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4A1055275AFC453936471AF40EB69BB4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="remark and differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D13C96F597A4136414E58F057D3E5955" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Remark and differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CAB3CD772AE8871B55243A6D2467B07E" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
The confinement of this undoubtedly new species to a pulmonate family is not easy, because only a single, dead collected shell is available. Although it looks somewhat similar to species from the family 
<taxonomicName id="107DC7CF0393C787F42F29110ABA72F3" authorityName="Morse" authorityYear="1864" class="Gastropoda" family="Punctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Eupulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Punctidae</taxonomicName>
(with 
<taxonomicName id="CBC9FAD38697631D03A3FF3FC9A39E9B" baseAuthorityName="Draparnaud" baseAuthorityYear="1801" class="Gastropoda" family="Punctidae" genus="Punctum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Eupulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pygmaeum">
<emphasis id="F633E5D0475550D5EFBF2A61A4E38854" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Punctum pygmaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Draparnaud, 1801) known from Turkey), we have decided to place it in 
<taxonomicName id="8954DA42985407CB6A00E7F38160DF2C" authorityName="T.Cockerell" authorityYear="1891" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Pristilomatidae</taxonomicName>
because of the pale color of the shell.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A13EE36485B22712C0C67658932EE1C4" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Under a conchological point of view, a classification within the pristilomatid genus 
<taxonomicName id="9984E203F51F1968EEAFECBD9AAADF29" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Lindbergia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="729949276366004E373C23AE4B7743B4" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Lindbergia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Riedel, 1959, would also be possible, as the two genera can only be differentiated by the anatomy of their genital organs (
<bibRefCitation id="67D603337D78629B0993222854889B73" author="Riedel, A" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="10" pageNumber="27" pagination="89 - 117" refId="B18" refString="Riedel, A, 1959. Zonitidae (Gastropoda) zebrane w Grecji przez dra K. Lindberga. Annales Zoologici 18: 89 - 117" title="Zonitidae (Gastropoda) zebrane w Grecji przez dra K. Lindberga." volume="18" year="1959">Riedel 1959</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="247E49D32B3BDD373CAAAE2A0AFB3492" author="Oerstan, A" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="10" pageNumber="27" refId="B16" refString="Oerstan, A, Yildirim, MZ, 2004. Borlumastus gen. Nov. (Gastropoda, Pulmonata, Enidae), a new land snail genus from Turkey. Basteria, Leiden, 68 (4/6): 125-129." title="Borlumastus gen. Nov. (Gastropoda, Pulmonata, Enidae), a new land snail genus from Turkey. Basteria, Leiden, 68 (4 / 6): 125 - 129." year="2004">1960</bibRefCitation>
). We here confine this species to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="F30B58D48213DE92161A915F38F815AC" authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1833" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4C4A3BB12AF68D2DD60F4C18B98E2575" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fitzinger, 1833, because of its overall conchological resemblance to other species comprised in this genus. An assignment to 
<taxonomicName id="F6C4F7DAB8976F30749FA4CE6BAD90F8" class="Gastropoda" family="Oxychilidae" genus="Oxychilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90408E027F15F163669032DF3C49C88E" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Oxychilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fitzinger is less probable, as even the smallest species of 
<taxonomicName id="10BE972A446DB0F7CD8B8F2E7B862BC9" class="Gastropoda" family="Oxychilidae" genus="Oxychilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F32B8D3F4B31A77C72740E8F0AD8BA36" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Oxychilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are clearly larger than the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5151D31DEF5736E57703FA57D6B0CAF2" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName id="65EFC2FC9CF14FDEC8A8746CDBF9E552" authorityName="Gümüş &amp; Neubert" authorityYear="2012" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gostelii">
<emphasis id="3855BCD7056E6B517389890CC955C25F" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea gostelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n. differs from all 
<taxonomicName id="AAEE762EDC94736E95DFE668BA518C89" authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1833" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="22F119CC0BC6285C0598144A4E44D910" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from Turkey by the presences of riblets and a spiral sculpture. It somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName id="BF0C867267FAC6AFD4F83B123FEE6793" authorityName="O. Paget" authorityYear="1976" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="riedeliana">
<emphasis id="B5DF3A8F61B036E7C442D696C5A8CB80" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea riedeliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the spire in 
<taxonomicName id="FB98ABA4A9138E6C5590C6AB882925EE" authorityName="O. Paget" authorityYear="1976" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="riedeliana">
<emphasis id="CB1C28AF09E26E4BE6153BD231B986FC" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea riedeliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more elevated. 
<taxonomicName id="22A9619B6F4310166ED7069B0E6B4AF0" class="Gastropoda" family="Pristilomatidae" genus="Vitrea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Pulmonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="riedeli">
<emphasis id="123291F6A391D10F446BC5733C28BCD7" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Vitrea riedeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a smooth shell with a wider umbilicus with a deeper suture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="16114A3D65286B6AF9652BD033A4B9EB" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">This species was found during our survey in 2006 below a large limestone rock face of probably about 50 m of height. Probably, this species lives subterraneously, and a more targeted search in the accumulated soil of carstic crevices will yield some living specimens, which then will help to corroborate the taxonomic position of this new species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
